Just for your peace of mind, I'd be sure you and your husband are at least minimally sprayed with a DEET-free repellent -- hair, clothes, even luggage. I'm a little farther south than Columbia, and at high altitude, but that's what I would do if travelling to a lower altitude. (We have no problem with mosquitos up here, but with all the street dogs, I have been bitten by other parasitic bugs, and it's not pleasant, especially since I have bad allergic reactions.)
 ;
Also... Off the Zika topic, If you don't already take a multi-strain probiotic with at least 20 billion live cultures, I would gradually start doing so as a preventative measure. Sanitation and hygiene standards -- even if you're not eating street food -- are a lot different down here and not nearly as strict. Whenever I eat something I haven't prepared myself, I'll be sure to take one. On the rare occasions that I've eaten something 'questionable', I'll double up. It's difficult to OD on probiotics (from what I've read) so I've even taken up to 6 in a 24 hour period. I've now lived in South America for 2.5 years. I believe the probiotics have made the difference between having G.I. distress 4x in the first year (including giardiasis, ugh), to not having any problems for over a year (and I'm quite picky about where I'll eat to begin with).
 ;
Take some preventative measures so you could leave your worries behind, and enjoy your trip to Bogotá!
